EDA and Visualization¶

EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis) is the next step in the work of the data scientist. We will conduct an in-depth analysis of the data, and through visualizations, we can begin to answer questions and draw conclusions.

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib as mpl
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
%matplotlib inline

We will start by adding a decade column derived from the year column. This column will be useful in data analysis.

In [2]:
df = pd.read_csv('full_after_processing.csv')
df = df[['artist', 'song', 'genres', 'year', 'key', 'mode', 'duration', 'bpm']]  # Dropping the 'Unnamed: 0' column
decades = [((s//10)*10) for s in df['year'].copy()]
df['decade'] = pd.Series(decades)
df.head()

Single variable visualization¶

In [3]:
colors = ['#ADEFD1FF', '#00203FFF', '#B8D991FF', '#F8E6A6FF']
df['mode'].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', colors=colors)
plt.title('Major(1) and minor(0) songs')
Out[3]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Major(1) and minor(0) songs')

As we can see, the majority of the songs are on a major scale.

We will examine the distribution of songs in the data by decades.

In [4]:
df['decade'].value_counts().plot(kind='barh', color=colors[1])
plt.xlabel('Count')
plt.ylabel('Decade')
plt.title('Number of songs in each decade')
Out[4]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Number of songs in each decade')

Most of the songs are between the years 1980-2019, Let's look in a higher resolution.

In [5]:
df['year'].hist(bins=50, color=colors[1])
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
Out[5]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Frequency')

Same results.

The next thing we will look at is the bpm distribution of the song.

In [6]:
df['bpm'].hist(bins=50, color=colors[1])
plt.xlabel('Bpm')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
Out[6]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Frequency')

Most of the songs are at bpm of 75-150. We notice a jump in the number of songs at 120 bpm. Why? After researching online, it seems that there are 2 theories.

  1. 120 is exactly 2 beats per second, so the human ear is used to this rhythm.

  2. Most of the popular digital music production software comes at a default bpm of 120.

In order to check the second theory, we will can look at the number of 120bpm songs over the years.

In [7]:
(df[df['bpm'] == 120])['year'].hist(bins=50, color=colors[1])
Out[7]:
<AxesSubplot:>

It seems that there has been an increase in songs at the rate of 120 in the mid-2000s. This increase reinforces the theory that the reason behind songs at this pace is the digital production software that gained momentum during this period.

Cross Tabulation¶

We will use Cross Tabulation to test the relationship between two categorical variables. We will start by looking at the division into musical genres by decade.

In [8]:
ct1 = pd.crosstab(df['decade'], df['genres'], normalize='index')
ct1.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(9,4), color=colors)
Out[8]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='decade'>

It can be seen that until the 70s-80s pop and rock were the only and leading music genres from the categories we chose. Then dance and hip hop songs started to gain momentum but are still in the minority compared to pop and rock.

The next thing we will check out is the mode of the song (major/minor) and the music genre.

In [9]:
ct2 = pd.crosstab(df['genres'], df['mode'], normalize='index')
ct2.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(9,4), color=colors)
Out[9]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='genres'>

We can see that in all genres major songs are leading. In Dance and Hip Hop, the modes are more balanced.

We will use violin plot too look at the duration of the songs distribution among the decades.

In [10]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
sns.violinplot(x=df['decade'], y=df['duration'], normalize='index', grid=True)
plt.yticks(np.arange(0, 1750, 125))
plt.grid()

As we can see, the mean duration of the song in each decade doubled from the 50s to the 70s and stayed the same from the 70s to 2010s.

Let's use a line plot to see the same connection. But now, we will also add a plot to the bpm feature.

In [11]:
graph = df.groupby(['decade']).mean()[['bpm', 'duration']]
graph.plot(color=colors)
Out[11]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='decade'>

there is no drastic change in the mean bpm feature among the years.

Scatter Plot¶

We will use a scatter plot to map the songs using the bpm-suration axis system. We will color each genre a different color.

In [12]:
sns.scatterplot(x = 'duration', y = 'bpm', s = 7, hue = 'genres', data=df)

<AxesSubplot:xlabel='duration', ylabel='bpm'>
